Report: act_report¶

WeRateDogs - DATA ANALYSIS¶

Introduction¶

I'll be summarizing the analysis I did in my project notebook. The dataset that I analysed is the tweet archive of Twitter user @dog_rates, also known as WeRateDogs. WeRateDogs is a Twitter account that rates people's dogs with a humorous comment about the dog. These ratings almost always have a denominator of 10. The numerators, though? Almost always greater than 10 (like 11/10, 12/10, 13/10, etc). Why? Because "they're good dogs Brent." WeRateDogs has over 4 million followers and has received international media coverage.

Analysing the data¶

I have analysed the dataframes tweet_updated and image_updated and tweet_updated from the report after storing them into into a master .csv file – twitter_archive_master .csv. I have also analysed the data on 5 different questions of interest.

1. Comparison Of Average Rating Of Dog Stages¶

,

Observations:¶

  1. The pie chart shows that 66.34% of the dogs in this dataset are puppers followed by doggo, then floofer and at the bottom, puppo. From this, we can say that the reason for pupper having the lowest average rating, and puppo and floofer having the highest average rating is a result of the huge differences in their proportion in the dataset.
  2. The bar chart shows that puppo and floofer has the highest average rating while pupper has the lowest.
